    "summary": "\u201cThe future of millions of people in urban areas around the world are under pressure due to the different effects of climate change . At the same time there are opportunities to protect these areas through the application of knowledge and modern technology in combination with sustainable urban planning.\u201d\n\nIn recent years I have worked in Mexico on a major project for the city of Oaxaca. In a participation process with locals, and a good partnership with the Mexican government, we developed a Vision to Restore the Atoyac River. The vision developed a strategy to reinvigorate the river by improving the water quality and the ecosystems along its shoreline.  Due to the fact that the river flows through a large part of the city, this strategic approach has had a positive impact on the surrounding neighborhoods. This in turn triggered private and public investors to invest on projects along the shores of the river and in the neighborhoods.\n\nMy strength lies in the fact that I have experience with modern theories, practices and techniques, and I am familiar with the language and culture of different countries and continents. Communication is the most important factor in getting processes and projects off the ground. All my life I been drawing and visualizing the conditions of urban space, in this task (urban planning) is a great tool and is vital to inspiration and communication. I would like to use my expertise to help different projects in urban areas that are facing the pressures of climate change. \nMy experience and expertise is not only of value to Europe, I am open to projects in other parts of the world. I have lived and worked in South America and in New York for many years and in the Netherlands I successfully completed my Masters at The Berlage Institute and have worked on projects at home and abroad for the Dutch offices: Architecten Cie and Urhahn Urban Design.\n",
